---
import Editor from '../components/Editor.astro'
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import { SEED_FILES } from '../lib/seed-files.ts'
---
<Base title="Vár playground" description="Run Vár in the browser.">
  <main class="doc playground">
    <h1>playground</h1>
    <p>
      Edit the spec or the step definitions — both share one in-browser Vár language
      server, so the highlighting in the spec updates live as you change either file.
    </p>

    <p>
      TIP: Install the VSCode extension or the LSP server to get Vár in your own editor.
    </p>

    <h2>the spec</h2>
    <Editor uri="file:///hello.var.md" lang="markdown">{SEED_FILES['/hello.var.md']}</Editor>

    <h2>the step definitions</h2>
    <Editor uri="file:///01-hello.steps.ts" lang="typescript">{SEED_FILES['/01-hello.steps.ts']}</Editor>

    <p>
      If you have ever written a unit test, this will be familiar. The main difference between
      examples and unit tests are:

      <ul>
        <li>Examples are written in human language</li>
        <li>Examples often have 3 steps: a context, an action, and an expected outcome</li>
        <li>Each step is linked to a function through an expression</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
  /* The playground needs a wider column than the prose measure: code editors
     are cramped at 46rem and overflow horizontally. Widen the container and
     trim the side padding so the editors get room. */
  main.playground {
    max-width: 62rem;
    padding-left: var(--ax-space-16);
    padding-right: var(--ax-space-16);
  }
</style>
